WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.480 --> 00:00:06.240
- Mike Wozny is here and we're
gonna talk about bodybuilders

00:00:06.240 --> 00:00:09.210
and what bodybuilders need to learn

00:00:09.210 --> 00:00:11.520
that they haven't learned yet.

00:00:11.520 --> 00:00:15.420
And a lot of things that
get published in research,

00:00:15.420 --> 00:00:19.140
a lot of things that are
common knowledge with academia

00:00:19.140 --> 00:00:22.260
don't end up always getting to the people

00:00:22.260 --> 00:00:24.300
who are trying to make
results happen in the gym.

00:00:24.300 --> 00:00:27.390
Gyms are not really incentivized
to give people results,

00:00:27.390 --> 00:00:29.010
they typically just give people access

00:00:29.010 --> 00:00:30.990
or selling personal training

00:00:30.990 --> 00:00:33.930
and they don't really care what you do

00:00:33.930 --> 00:00:35.850
and even if you're being ineffective

00:00:35.850 --> 00:00:39.270
and that's too bad,
because there's certainly

00:00:39.270 --> 00:00:42.600
more effective approaches
than people are doing now.

00:00:42.600 --> 00:00:45.330
One of the things I regularly say is,

00:00:45.330 --> 00:00:48.570
if regular weightlifting
and cardio for weight loss

00:00:48.570 --> 00:00:51.180
works so well, where
are all the fit people?

00:00:51.180 --> 00:00:52.013
- Right.

00:00:52.013 --> 00:00:56.010
- Yeah, pretty much everybody
with impressive physique

00:00:56.010 --> 00:00:58.020
has a supplement contract.

00:00:58.020 --> 00:00:59.146
- Yeah.

00:00:59.146 --> 00:01:01.170
- And it just shows you how rare that is,

00:01:01.170 --> 00:01:03.660
it's really rare to be in great shape.

00:01:03.660 --> 00:01:05.850
And a lot of people
should be in great shape,

00:01:05.850 --> 00:01:07.350
millions of people
should be in great shape,

00:01:07.350 --> 00:01:09.870
but they're going about doing it wrong.

00:01:09.870 --> 00:01:12.840
So let's talk about Mike, your journey,

00:01:12.840 --> 00:01:17.100
when you started moving away from weights.

00:01:17.100 --> 00:01:21.720
- Moving away from weights,
I guess it really started

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:25.420
four years ago when I was
getting desperate 'cause

00:01:26.790 --> 00:01:31.710
I hadn't competed at that
point in around four years

00:01:31.710 --> 00:01:35.940
because of a knee injury that
kept egging me from squatting.

00:01:35.940 --> 00:01:36.773
- Yeah.

00:01:37.648 --> 00:01:39.030
- A quadricep tendon issue,

00:01:39.030 --> 00:01:44.030
I had hurt it and every
time I would rehabilitate it

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:47.073
and working my way up again,

00:01:49.080 --> 00:01:51.420
I eventually just would start swelling up

00:01:51.420 --> 00:01:52.560
and there was nothing...

00:01:52.560 --> 00:01:56.250
I felt absolutely defeated
and the funny thing is,

00:01:56.250 --> 00:01:59.140
that's when Phil Hernan had met you

00:01:59.980 --> 00:02:03.150
and I had this small interaction with you

00:02:03.150 --> 00:02:06.003
and you talked about
balance and the bands.

00:02:06.840 --> 00:02:11.250
And then I started paying
attention to the band thing,

00:02:11.250 --> 00:02:12.900
'cause back when I was younger,

00:02:12.900 --> 00:02:15.870
all bands were these
surgical tubing things

00:02:15.870 --> 00:02:16.713
that we used to pump up-

00:02:16.713 --> 00:02:19.233
- Yeah, bands used to be a joke.

00:02:20.130 --> 00:02:22.050
Or they're great for rehab,

00:02:22.050 --> 00:02:23.940
like an outward rotation movement

00:02:23.940 --> 00:02:25.380
where you just outwardly rotate.

00:02:25.380 --> 00:02:27.870
So just to rebuild your rotator cuff

00:02:27.870 --> 00:02:29.526
from surgery or something.

00:02:29.526 --> 00:02:30.359
- Yeah.

00:02:30.359 --> 00:02:31.500
- Yeah.
- Exactly.

00:02:31.500 --> 00:02:33.510
And I had a lot of shoulder issues

00:02:33.510 --> 00:02:35.580
from obviously bench pressing,

00:02:35.580 --> 00:02:37.800
most guys that have shoulder issues,

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:39.633
it's from bench pressing.

00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:42.180
- And they're not doing anything wrong,

00:02:42.180 --> 00:02:44.550
that's just what bench pressing
does to your shoulders.

00:02:44.550 --> 00:02:45.383
- Correct, yeah.

00:02:45.383 --> 00:02:47.340
You get most load in the stretch position

00:02:47.340 --> 00:02:49.830
and it eventually is gonna tear 'em up.

00:02:49.830 --> 00:02:53.160
Started adding bands to my lifts

00:02:53.160 --> 00:02:55.450
and I remember I was
training this one girl

00:02:56.520 --> 00:03:00.180
and I had her doing lateral
raises with light dumbbells.

00:03:00.180 --> 00:03:03.250
And then I would put this
band around her wrists

00:03:04.290 --> 00:03:06.663
and her delts just started growing.

00:03:08.442 --> 00:03:11.160
And they actually got remarkably

00:03:11.160 --> 00:03:13.320
and we started adding
bands to bench press.

00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:15.060
They started adding bands.

00:03:15.060 --> 00:03:18.300
I started doing double
leg work on a balance

00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:23.300
and that caused my hips
to engage properly.

00:03:23.760 --> 00:03:26.700
I started using my
abductors, the adductors,

00:03:26.700 --> 00:03:27.990
the glutes that, you know,

00:03:27.990 --> 00:03:30.090
everything came in together and

00:03:30.090 --> 00:03:32.730
it held everything in a place where

00:03:32.730 --> 00:03:35.880
in order to balance perfectly,
I had to do a perfect squat.

00:03:35.880 --> 00:03:38.313
You know, I couldn't put a load forward.

00:03:39.420 --> 00:03:40.253
I didn't have my-

00:03:40.253 --> 00:03:42.769
- Exercise on an unseeable surface,

00:03:42.769 --> 00:03:44.460
and you're gonna fire everything.

00:03:44.460 --> 00:03:45.510
- Yeah.

00:03:45.510 --> 00:03:48.690
Everything was just equally tuned in

00:03:48.690 --> 00:03:51.870
and my joints weren't
getting, there was no pain.

00:03:51.870 --> 00:03:54.930
So then I started working
deeper and deeper and deeper.

00:03:54.930 --> 00:03:57.840
And then I started adding
a band over my shoulders.

00:03:57.840 --> 00:04:00.780
Well eventually what I
would start doing is,

00:04:00.780 --> 00:04:04.380
going back to squatting, then
I would get set back again.

00:04:04.380 --> 00:04:05.213
- Yeah, sure.

00:04:05.213 --> 00:04:08.550
- I kind of had thought
competing was gonna be

00:04:08.550 --> 00:04:11.130
the end of it all for me, it was done.

00:04:11.130 --> 00:04:13.293
I was getting older, screw it,

00:04:14.430 --> 00:04:19.430
and I was open to still training guys,

00:04:19.470 --> 00:04:22.770
but I was working these long
hours in these weld shops

00:04:22.770 --> 00:04:25.830
and I was training.

00:04:25.830 --> 00:04:28.410
I was still going to the gym, but my legs,

00:04:28.410 --> 00:04:30.240
I would just do what I could.

00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:33.060
And it was always a depressing thing,

00:04:33.060 --> 00:04:35.170
but it was well over a year ago now

00:04:36.570 --> 00:04:41.570
I started doing single leg work
and just adding bands to it.

00:04:43.650 --> 00:04:45.909
And all these guys are telling me,

00:04:45.909 --> 00:04:48.813
oh, I've worked with those
bands, they don't do anything.

00:04:49.650 --> 00:04:51.330
But they never really
just worked with bands

00:04:51.330 --> 00:04:52.230
and kept doing it.

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:54.840
- They didn't really give a shot.

00:04:54.840 --> 00:04:58.470
They threw a band on
something they were doing and-

00:04:58.470 --> 00:05:02.063
- Yeah, they throw it on the weight.

00:05:02.063 --> 00:05:03.930
You throw it on a weight and then,

00:05:03.930 --> 00:05:06.270
people talk about how that
gets you between plateaus.

00:05:06.270 --> 00:05:08.220
Well that's because the
muscles pushing harder

00:05:08.220 --> 00:05:09.690
through the whole movement,

00:05:09.690 --> 00:05:12.453
and it's gonna hyper trophy
more and it gets stronger.

00:05:15.420 --> 00:05:17.790
It's not strengthening
the end of the movement,

00:05:17.790 --> 00:05:21.456
it's strengthening the muscle
altogether, it's one muscle,

00:05:21.456 --> 00:05:22.830
- Well, you fire more tissue

00:05:22.830 --> 00:05:24.780
when you're in your stronger range.

00:05:24.780 --> 00:05:25.613
- Yeah.

00:05:26.534 --> 00:05:27.367
- I mean, it's not like-

00:05:27.367 --> 00:05:28.740
- All these guys are talking about how

00:05:28.740 --> 00:05:30.330
you're creating this kinetic energy.

00:05:30.330 --> 00:05:32.520
It'll throw it at the end or
whatever you're strengthening

00:05:32.520 --> 00:05:34.500
the end of your movement or whatever.

00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:35.333
I'm like-

00:05:35.333 --> 00:05:36.723
- True, and there's-

00:05:36.723 --> 00:05:38.307
- In the muscle period, your maximum,

00:05:38.307 --> 00:05:41.100
the amount you can go lift is going up

00:05:41.100 --> 00:05:44.180
and so obviously knew Phil Hern very well.

00:05:44.180 --> 00:05:45.457
- Yeah, one of my really good friends.

00:05:45.457 --> 00:05:47.520
- He'd been one of my very good friends

00:05:47.520 --> 00:05:49.920
for the last 12 years.

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:52.443
And I just trusted him completely.

00:05:54.120 --> 00:05:56.220
He never steered me wrong.

00:05:56.220 --> 00:05:58.920
And he had been doing the band pretty much

00:05:58.920 --> 00:06:02.493
that's it for the last,
I'm gonna say three years.

00:06:03.870 --> 00:06:06.427
- Yeah, that's how long
we were working on that.

00:06:06.427 --> 00:06:11.427
- And he trained Cedric
McMillan with bands and,

00:06:11.700 --> 00:06:14.070
Cedric was very impressed with it.

00:06:14.070 --> 00:06:14.903
- Yeah.

00:06:15.990 --> 00:06:17.550
I got some great pictures on the website

00:06:17.550 --> 00:06:19.540
and Cedric using the X3.

00:06:19.540 --> 00:06:20.727
- Okay, yeah, yeah.

00:06:20.727 --> 00:06:22.920
- Now he graduated to the X3.

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:23.753
- Okay (laughs).

00:06:24.810 --> 00:06:28.950
And then he had introduced
me just briefly to

00:06:28.950 --> 00:06:32.260
another guy, you and I had
actually discussed earlier

00:06:33.990 --> 00:06:35.430
and all these guys look great

00:06:35.430 --> 00:06:36.870
and they're just using these bands

00:06:36.870 --> 00:06:39.780
and I'm like, okay, well,
I'm gonna give it a try.

00:06:39.780 --> 00:06:41.940
And I actually got a lot of backlash.

00:06:41.940 --> 00:06:43.500
I couldn't believe the amount of people

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:45.930
that just thought I was completely stupid.

00:06:45.930 --> 00:06:47.640
I had friends getting hold of me,

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:49.050
are you're not body building anymore?

00:06:49.050 --> 00:06:52.023
I'm just wondering what
avenue you're going down.

00:06:53.379 --> 00:06:55.650
And I said, well, I hurt so bad.

00:06:55.650 --> 00:06:58.920
And I'm willing to try anything, you know?

00:06:58.920 --> 00:06:59.753
- Right.

00:07:01.230 --> 00:07:02.160
- If Phil believes that

00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:04.443
even though he might
be crazy at the moment,

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:06.480
he's never steered me wrong,

00:07:06.480 --> 00:07:08.370
and Phil's not stupid by any means.

00:07:08.370 --> 00:07:11.130
- And as we found out,
Phil was never crazy.

00:07:11.130 --> 00:07:14.500
And he's actually brilliant
because he can speak out

00:07:15.810 --> 00:07:17.193
the right thing to do.

00:07:18.468 --> 00:07:20.970
- And then so I'm doing the
single leg work, adding bands.

00:07:20.970 --> 00:07:24.390
And then Phil finally said,
"Mike," it was about a year ago.

00:07:24.390 --> 00:07:25.747
He said, "You're not
gonna know what bands do

00:07:25.747 --> 00:07:27.267
"unless you just use them."

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:29.160
- Only.

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:29.993
- Yeah.

00:07:29.993 --> 00:07:33.033
Just do 'em, I'm like, okay, screw it.

00:07:34.440 --> 00:07:37.590
I started using just bands
and finding different ways.

00:07:37.590 --> 00:07:39.340
And what he did was he said, "Mike,

00:07:42.452 --> 00:07:43.740
"you're scientific, you like to dig in."

00:07:43.740 --> 00:07:45.697
He said, "Try a bunch of
stuff and get back to me

00:07:45.697 --> 00:07:47.297
"and see what you come up with."

00:07:48.780 --> 00:07:51.870
Well, I'm doing all this crazy balancing

00:07:51.870 --> 00:07:54.000
and putting bands on
everything and rigging 'em all

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.823
over the gym and trying
this and that and whatever.

00:07:57.690 --> 00:08:00.900
And then I'm starting to
figure 'em out in my head,

00:08:00.900 --> 00:08:02.400
and I'm thinking, okay,

00:08:02.400 --> 00:08:05.477
so let's say a really
easy thing to remember,

00:08:05.477 --> 00:08:06.993
I think it was a curl.

00:08:08.100 --> 00:08:10.740
And it you'd start out with a weight,

00:08:10.740 --> 00:08:12.033
like say a barbell curve.

00:08:13.349 --> 00:08:15.787
And when you start out,

00:08:15.787 --> 00:08:19.740
you's see you got 80 pounds
there with a barbell curl.

00:08:19.740 --> 00:08:24.740
And as you come up, it's 80
pounds right out of the hole.

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:28.163
And then actually after
you pass halfway up,

00:08:28.163 --> 00:08:31.200
because it's static,
resistance and gravity,

00:08:31.200 --> 00:08:34.380
you start to lose, you know,
and then you have to bend-

00:08:34.380 --> 00:08:36.630
- When you approach the
fully contracted position

00:08:36.630 --> 00:08:38.100
the way it actually goes down

00:08:38.100 --> 00:08:41.640
because the lever arm is
becoming closer to the origin.

00:08:41.640 --> 00:08:43.350
- And the weird part is, in your head

00:08:43.350 --> 00:08:45.690
you don't feel this weight in your hand.

00:08:45.690 --> 00:08:48.510
So you kind of, at first it's weird.

00:08:48.510 --> 00:08:49.860
But then I started noticing

00:08:51.480 --> 00:08:53.040
less paying attention to the weight,

00:08:53.040 --> 00:08:56.250
I started paying attention
to the way my muscle felt.

00:08:56.250 --> 00:08:58.980
- That's right, 'cause you
don't have a weight to drop.

00:08:58.980 --> 00:09:00.000
- Yeah.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:03.946
- You start to focus on
the muscle (indistinct).

00:09:03.946 --> 00:09:05.970
- You start, and it's
20 pounds of resistance.

00:09:05.970 --> 00:09:07.800
And it's kind of funny feeling at first.

00:09:07.800 --> 00:09:08.633
- Yeah.

00:09:08.633 --> 00:09:09.466
- But as you come up,

00:09:09.466 --> 00:09:12.447
it gets to the point where
it's dumb to a dead stop

00:09:12.447 --> 00:09:14.940
and it is the hardest
contraction you've ever felt

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:16.290
in your entire life.

00:09:16.290 --> 00:09:17.127
And guys would tell me, oh yeah,

00:09:17.127 --> 00:09:18.840
you can get a real good pump with that,

00:09:18.840 --> 00:09:20.580
but it ain't gonna build any muscle.

00:09:20.580 --> 00:09:23.703
And I started thinking, well,
resistance is resistance.

00:09:24.683 --> 00:09:26.312
- Muscle doesn't know
what you're contracting.

00:09:26.312 --> 00:09:27.900
- My muscle doesn't have a fricking clue

00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:29.010
what's going on there.

00:09:29.010 --> 00:09:31.180
And not only that is it wasn't

00:09:32.940 --> 00:09:36.210
limited to a linear plane and gravity

00:09:36.210 --> 00:09:37.710
pulling it straight down.

00:09:37.710 --> 00:09:39.720
This stuff could go all over the place.

00:09:39.720 --> 00:09:41.520
So the stability of it was,

00:09:41.520 --> 00:09:42.918
pretty soon your whole,

00:09:42.918 --> 00:09:45.360
you're stabilizing to stay in it

00:09:45.360 --> 00:09:47.820
and then your muscle is getting detached.

00:09:47.820 --> 00:09:50.280
- And then the more
stabilization requiring

00:09:50.280 --> 00:09:53.190
for growth hormone gets upregulated.

00:09:53.190 --> 00:09:56.460
It all kind of dovetails together

00:09:56.460 --> 00:09:58.170
all the principles
we've been talking about

00:09:58.170 --> 00:10:00.150
when you go to fatigue

00:10:00.150 --> 00:10:03.030
using a strong level
of variable resistance.

00:10:03.030 --> 00:10:04.200
- Correct, yep.

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:08.310
And I started thinking about it

00:10:08.310 --> 00:10:12.240
and every rep would get a little shorter,

00:10:12.240 --> 00:10:13.710
you know what I mean?

00:10:13.710 --> 00:10:14.543
I started thinking, well,

00:10:14.543 --> 00:10:16.920
rep ranges don't matter as much anymore

00:10:16.920 --> 00:10:21.920
because when you use a set
load, when you fail at the top,

00:10:22.050 --> 00:10:24.720
you're definitely not gonna
get it out of the bottom.

00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:25.710
It's done.

00:10:25.710 --> 00:10:28.860
Then at that point, you'd
have to drop a weight

00:10:28.860 --> 00:10:30.720
and then do a drop set.

00:10:30.720 --> 00:10:33.090
- Right, and then that
discontinues the contraction,

00:10:33.090 --> 00:10:36.338
blood starts rushing in
to recover the muscle.

00:10:36.338 --> 00:10:38.250
And you really don't have the benefit,

00:10:38.250 --> 00:10:40.200
you have no hypoxic benefit.

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:43.020
You're not gonna change
your myostatin levels.

00:10:43.020 --> 00:10:45.900
I mean, basically your drop
set just like everything up.

00:10:45.900 --> 00:10:46.733
- Yeah.

00:10:47.790 --> 00:10:49.530
Even it does create a better pump.

00:10:49.530 --> 00:10:53.790
And they've proven that
the pump lowers myostatin.

00:10:53.790 --> 00:10:55.440
Obviously, 'cause it's hitting the ceiling

00:10:55.440 --> 00:10:57.030
of that muscle, stretching it.

00:10:57.030 --> 00:10:59.430
And it's like, well, we're
gonna have to expand.

00:11:00.690 --> 00:11:05.370
But so let's say at the first
rep that you hit this wall

00:11:05.370 --> 00:11:07.950
at 100 pounds and pretty
soon it's 99 pounds,

00:11:07.950 --> 00:11:12.060
and it's 98.6 pounds and as you come up,

00:11:12.060 --> 00:11:13.410
you recruit all these fibers,

00:11:13.410 --> 00:11:15.570
you're recruiting fibers
into the contraction

00:11:15.570 --> 00:11:18.660
rather than just out of the bottom, right?

00:11:18.660 --> 00:11:22.830
So all these fibers,

00:11:22.830 --> 00:11:26.250
they get contracted and
then they start failing

00:11:26.250 --> 00:11:28.170
from the strongest.

00:11:28.170 --> 00:11:30.270
And pretty soon you're
getting about halfway,

00:11:30.270 --> 00:11:32.790
and the most static holds,

00:11:32.790 --> 00:11:35.970
you're just holding the weight
that you can normally lift,

00:11:35.970 --> 00:11:37.350
but you can pull against it.

00:11:37.350 --> 00:11:38.700
It's like you're hitting a wall.

00:11:38.700 --> 00:11:40.230
It's frustrating for a lot of people

00:11:40.230 --> 00:11:41.250
'cause they don't understand the-

00:11:41.250 --> 00:11:43.263
- It definitely feels different.

00:11:44.850 --> 00:11:47.013
When developing the X3,

00:11:49.170 --> 00:11:51.570
I definitely had the same,

00:11:51.570 --> 00:11:54.540
it's funny 'cause I get by
the trolls that were like,

00:11:54.540 --> 00:11:55.770
oh, weight lifting,

00:11:55.770 --> 00:11:57.120
I like the way it feels or whatever.

00:11:57.120 --> 00:12:00.180
And I'm like, ugh, I guess
results don't matter.

00:12:00.180 --> 00:12:04.320
But I get it because when
I develop my prototype-

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:05.340
- It feels formal.

00:12:05.340 --> 00:12:08.130
- Yeah, because you like seeing that

00:12:08.130 --> 00:12:12.903
big amount of iron
moving around on a bench.

00:12:13.830 --> 00:12:17.250
I remember the first time
I did 225 for repetitions,

00:12:17.250 --> 00:12:18.750
it was like, wow.

00:12:18.750 --> 00:12:22.680
I really liked seeing that
weight move, I felt cool.

